<div id="review_110917712" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/110917712" />
    <a title="Bevans" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3988199-bevans"><img alt="Bevans" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1288556462p2/3988199.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/110917712?book_show_action=true">Jul 10, 2010</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Bevans" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Bevans" href="/user/show/3988199-bevans">Bevans</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3988199-bevans?shelf=to-reread">to-reread</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3988199-bevans?shelf=favorites">favorites</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer110917712" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9274782034661235177">This book isn’t concerned with the truth of claims made by religions, but is merely interested in examining belief from cultural, behavioral, psychological, philosophical, and scientific perspectives.<br/><br/>The big question here is: why does religion exist? What purpose does it serve? What aspects of religion can be explained by science, and what makes religions similar and different?<br/><br/>The book covers much that Daniel Dennett’s book &quot;Breaking the Spell: Religion as a Natural Phenomenon&quot; does, but Shermer</span>
  <span id="freeText9274782034661235177" style="display:none">This book isn’t concerned with the truth of claims made by religions, but is merely interested in examining belief from cultural, behavioral, psychological, philosophical, and scientific perspectives.<br /><br />The big question here is: why does religion exist? What purpose does it serve? What aspects of religion can be explained by science, and what makes religions similar and different?<br /><br />The book covers much that Daniel Dennett’s book "Breaking the Spell: Religion as a Natural Phenomenon" does, but Shermer’s writing style is far easier to follow (I was only able to get about 90 pages into BtS before I stopped). Dennett’s book is probably more thorough, but Shermer is more accessible.<br /><br />This book taught me a great deal about the origins of religious thought, as well as how people think in general, and how our thinking behaves in ways we don’t expect it to.</span>
  <a data-text-id="9274782034661235177" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


